r the Expo.\r\n\r\nWho is AGC? The Associated General Contractors of America is the leading association for the construction industry. AGC represents more than 26,000 firms, including over 6,500 of Americas leading general contractors, and over 9,000 specialty-contracting firms. More than 10,500 service providers and suppliers are also associated with AGC, all through a nationwide network of chapters.\r\n\r\n<b><a href=\"https://www.eiseverywhere.com/ereg/index.php?eventid=371661\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">REGISTER NOW</a></b>','AGC Annual Conference 2019','','inherit','closed','closed','','590-revision-v1','','','2019-02-01 17:09:58','2019-02-01 17:09:58','',590,'http://localhost:8888/moffitt/?p=592',0,'revision','',0),(593,1,'2019-02-01 17:13:41','2019-02-01 17:13:41','On the heels of the longest partial government shutdown in history in January 2019, the jobs report for that period is a stunner.\r\n\r\nAnd the construction industry is not immune from a little good newsbeing up 52k for the month. Manufacturing is up 13k. Construction pay, however, dropped by four tenths of a percent (0.4).\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nNationwide, 304,000 jobs were added to the economywell ahead of an expectation of 165,000and the overall unemployment rate sits right at 4%. This keeps the unemployment figure within the federal governments definition of<a href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/fullemployment.asp\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">full employment</a>.\r\n\r\nThe Bureau of Labor Statistics states in its report that total nonfarm payroll employment increased by 304,000 in January, and the unemployment rate edged up to 4.0 percent. Job gains occurred in several industries, including leisure and hospitality, construction, health care, and transportation and warehousing.\r\n\r\nThe details are all in the<a href=\"https://www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm\" data-blogger-escaped-target=\"_blank\">BLS report</a>, but please read the write-up by Yahoo News for the good news in plain English:\r\n\r\n<b>U.S. economy added more jobs than expected in January</b>\r\n\r\nEmily McCormick | Yahoo Finance | February 1, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://finance.yahoo.com/news/payrolls-jobs-report-january-2019-230417259.html\">https://finance.yahoo.com/news/payrolls-jobs-report-january-2019-230417259.html</a>\r\n\r\n<i>The rise in Januarys unemployment rate was also due in part to an increase in the labor force participation rate, which climbed to 63.2% from 63.1% in December. Januarys participation level marks the highest since 2013.</i>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<b>RELATED</b>\r\n\r\n<b>U.S. Payrolls Rise 304,000 as Wage Gains Cool Amid Shutdown</b>\r\n\r\nBy Sho Chandra | Bloomberg | February 1, 2019\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-01/u-s-payrolls-rise-304-000-while-wage-gains-cool-amid-shutdown\">https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-01/u-s-payrolls-rise-304-000-while-wage-gains-cool-amid-shutdown</a>\r\n\r\nU.S. hiring in January topped all forecasts while wage gains cooled and the government shutdown pushed up the unemployment rate, signaling job gains remain robust without major inflation pressures that would worry Federal Reserve officials.','January Jobs Report','','publish','closed','closed','','january-jobs-report','','','2019-02-01 17:13:41','2019-02-01 17:13:41','',0,'http://localhost:8888/moffitt/?p=593',0,'post','',0),(594,1,'2019-02-01 17:13:07','2019-02-01 17:13:07','','blog_4','','inherit','closed','closed','','blog_4','','','2019-02-01 17:13:07','2019-02-01 17:13:07','',593,'http://localhost:8888/moffitt/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/blog_4.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(595,1,'2019-02-01 17:13:41','2019-02-01 17:13:41','On the heels of the longest partial government shutdown in history in January 2019, the jobs report for that period is a stunner.\r\n\r\nAnd the construction industry is not immune from a little good newsbeing up 52k for the month. Manufacturing is up 13